"Richardson A.J., Schoeman D.S.","Climate impact on plankton ecosystems in the Northeast Atlantic",2004,"Science","305","5690",,"1609","1612",,,10.1126/science.1100958,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-4644324708&partnerID=40&md5=365d6e50d1c74c07f84e838fe9fb5dc1","Sir Alister Hardy Found. Ocean Sci., The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth, PL1 2PB, United Kingdom; Department of Zoology, University of Port Elizabeth, Port Elizabeth, South Africa","Richardson, A.J., Sir Alister Hardy Found. Ocean Sci., The Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth, PL1 2PB, United Kingdom; Schoeman, D.S., Department of Zoology, University of Port Elizabeth, Port Elizabeth, South Africa","It is now widely accepted that global warming is occurring, yet its effects on the world's largest ecosystem, the marine pelagic realm, are largely unknown. We show that sea surface warming in the Northeast Atlantic is accompanied by increasing phytoplankton abundance in cooler regions and decreasing phytoplankton abundance in warmer regions. This impact propagates up the food web (bottom-up control) through copepod herbivores to Zooplankton carnivores because of tight trophic coupling. Future warming is therefore likely to alter the spatial distribution of primary and secondary pelagic production, affecting ecosystem services and placing additional stress on already-depleted fish and mammal populations.",,"Climate change; Global warming; Marine applications; Plankton ecosystem; Trophic coupling; Ecosystems; climate effect; marine ecosystem; plankton; article; Atlantic Ocean; carnivore; climate change; fish; food web; greenhouse effect; herbivory; mammal; marine environment; nonhuman; pelagic zone; phytoplankton; priority journal; sea surface temperature; zooplankton; animal; climate; copepod; ecosystem; food chain; food industry; growth, development and aging; meta analysis; population dynamics; temperature; Atlantic Ocean; Atlantic Ocean (Northeast); Copepoda; Mammalia; sea water; Animals; Atlantic Ocean; Climate; Copepoda; Ecosystem; Fisheries; Fishes; Food Chain; Greenhouse Effect; Meta-Analysis; Phytoplankton; Population Dynamics; Seawater; Temperature; Zooplankton",,,,,,"Falkowski, P.G., Barber, R.T., Smetacek, V., (1998) Science, 281, p. 200; Roemmich, D., McGowan, J., (1995) Science, 267, p. 1324; Hughes, L., (2000) Trends Ecol. Evol., 15, p. 56; Beaugrand, G., Reid, P.C., Ibañez, F., Lindley, J.A., Edwards, M., (2002) Science, 296, p. 1692; Cury, P., (2000) ICES J. Mar. Sci., 57, p. 603; Aebischer, N.J., Coulson, J.C., Colebrook, J.M., (1990) Nature, 347, p. 753; Irigoien, X., Huisman, J., Harris, R.P., (2004) Nature, 429, p. 863; Daskalov, G.M., (2002) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 225, p. 53; Micheli, F., (1999) Science, 285, p. 1396; Shurin, J.B., (2002) Ecol. Lett., 5, p. 785; Reid, P.C., Colebrook, J.M., Matthews, J.B.L., Aiken, J., (2003) Prog. Oceanogr., 58, p. 117; Beaugrand, G., Brander, K.M., Lindley, J.A., Souissi, S., Reid, P.C., (2003) Nature, 426, p. 661; Worm, B., Myers, R.A., (2003) Ecology, 84, p. 162; noteBouman, H.A., (2003) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 258, p. 19; noteColebrook, J.M., (1975) Bull. Mar. Ecol., 8, p. 143; Pyper, B.J., Peterman, R.M., (1998) Can. J. Fish. Aquat. Sci., 55, p. 2127; notePlanque, B., Frédou, T., (1999) Can. J. Fish. Aquat. Sci., 56, p. 2069; Li, W.K.W., (2002) Nature, 419, p. 154; Carder, K.L., Chen, F.R., Lee, Z.P., Hawes, S.K., Kamykowski, D., (1999) J. Geophys. Res., 104, p. 5403; Sathyendranath, S., Cota, G., Stuart, V., Maass, H., Platt, T., (2001) Int. J. Remote Sens., 22, p. 249; Fromentin, J.-M., Planque, B., (1996) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 134, p. 111; Hurrell, J.W., (1995) Science, 269, p. 676; Cushing, D.H., (1989) J. Plankton Res., 11, p. 1; O'Brien, C.M., Fox, C.J., Planque, B., Casey, J., (2000) Nature, 404, p. 142; Parsons, L.S., Lear, W.H., (1999) Prog. Oceanogr., 49, p. 167; Houghton, J.T., (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge; www.sahfos.org","R